1 Overview

The dataset comes from the Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS), a health-related telephone survey, that collects data from U.S. residents about their life habits and risk behaviors regarding subjects’ health. BRFSS is a large health survey system that continuously completes more than 400,000 adult interviews each year. The dataset we will be using is the data from 2015.

The survey contains many health-related questions, which will be treated as attributes. The answers to each question are usually delivered as yes or no or not sure. In this analysis, we will use the data from 2015, to predict the attribute “TOLDHI2” as the target attribute. The corresponding question of “TOLDHI2” is “Have you EVER been told by a doctor, nurse, or another health professional that your blood cholesterol is high”. The answers are distributed to Yes, No, Don’t know, Refused. In this analysis, the distribution of the target attributes is only considers two classes: Yes and No, as a binary classification since the most of data belongs to these two classes. The original dataset has over 400k data and 330 attributes.

The removal of missing data relies on the percentage of missing data in each attribute. An attribute containing over 30% missing data will be removed. The rest of the missing data will be replaced by the mode of value in each attribute. Furthermore, the rest 143 attributes will be reduced to 30 attributes, through feature selections.

2.1 Remove attributes based on percentage of missing

# Identify attributes where the missing value percentage is greater than 30%
attributes_to_remove <- names(missing_percentage[missing_percentage > 30 & names(missing_percentage) != "MAXDRNKS"])

# Remove those attributes from the data frame
BRFS_cleaned <- BRFS[, !(names(BRFS) %in% attributes_to_remove)]

BRFS_cleaned <- BRFS_cleaned[ , -which(colnames(BRFS_cleaned) %in% c("_STATE", "FMONTH", "IDATE", "IMONTH", "IDAY", "IYEAR", "DISPCODE", "SEQNO", "_PSU"))]

The attributes with a missing value percentage greater than 30% are subsequently removed. Additionally, any attributes with ambiguous definitions are also eliminated to ensure the accuracy and interpretability of the results. After that, there are still 142 columns remaining.

2.2 Replace missing values for remaining variables

# Function to calculate the mode
getMode <- function(v) {
  uniqv <- unique(v)
  uniqv[which.max(tabulate(match(v, uniqv)))]
}

for (col in names(BRFS_cleaned)) {
  # Check if there are missing values in the column
  if (sum(is.na(BRFS_cleaned[[col]])) > 0) {
    # Calculate the mode for the current column
    mode_value <- getMode(BRFS_cleaned[[col]][!is.na(BRFS_cleaned[[col]])])
    # Replace NA values with the mode value
    BRFS_cleaned[[col]][is.na(BRFS_cleaned[[col]])] <- mode_value
  }
}
missing_percentage <- sapply(BRFS_cleaned, function(x) {
  round(sum(is.na(x)) / length(x) * 100, 3)
})

# Check after cleaning
all_zeros <- all(missing_percentage == 0)
all_zeros
## [1] TRUE

In this analysis, we’ve addressed the issue of missing data within the BRFS_cleaned dataset by employing a method that replaces any missing values in each column with the mode of that column. The mode was chosen because it maintains the statistical integrity of the data by aligning new entries with the most common existing values, thus minimizing the impact on the overall data distribution.

After implementing this imputation strategy, we verified the effectiveness of our approach by calculating the percentage of missing data in each column, ensuring that each is now zero percent. This confirmation ensures that the dataset is complete, allowing for more reliable and robust data analysis moving forward. The choice of the mode for imputation is particularly useful in categorical data where mean or median is not be applicable for categorical variable.

2.3 Feature selection

Feature selection is a pivotal step in data preprocessing, particularly when dealing with a dataset containing 143 columns, as in the case of our cleaned dataset. It reduces the risk of overfitting by eliminating irrelevant or redundant independent variables. Moreover, it can enhance the interpretability of the model, allowing for easier comprehension of key factors contributing to the classification.

Feature selection was conducted through a correlation-based filtering approach, starting with the calculation of a correlation matrix to measure the linear relationships among the dataset’s features. Focusing on ‘TOLDHI2’ as our target, we applied a predefined threshold to filter out relatively less irrelevant features. Specifically, we identified features with an absolute correlation coefficient above the threshold as significant. Those that have a moderate to strong linear association with the TOLDHI2 are likely to be informative predictors in a classification model.

The code below contains the significant features identified through correlation analysis with ‘TOLDHI2’. For an in-depth understanding of the data, a comprehensive Data Dictionary is provided. This dictionary, derived from the code book by Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System of the original author [1], is included in the Data Dictionary in the Appendix.

3 Classification methods

data <- read.csv('BRFS_feature_filtered.csv')
data <- data[,-1]
data$TOLDHI2 <- ifelse(data$TOLDHI2 == 2, 0, 1)  
data$TOLDHI2 <- as.factor(data$TOLDHI2)   

# Splitting the data into training (60%), validation (20%), and test (20%) sets
set.seed(5003)  # for reproducibility
split <- createDataPartition(data$TOLDHI2, p=0.6, list=FALSE)
training <- data[split,]
temp <- data[-split,]
split2 <- createDataPartition(temp$TOLDHI2, p=0.5, list=FALSE)
validation <- temp[split2,]
test <- temp[-split2,]

3.1 Naive Bayes

Bayesian networks are a type of probabilistic graphical model that represent the joint conditional probability distribution of a set of variables.

3.1.1 Data processing

Converts all columns except “X_BMI5”, “MAXDRNKS”, “MENTHLTH”, and “CHILDREN” into factors. The modified data will be categorical data. Removes a column named ‘X’ from the dataset.

Numerical variables “X_BMI5”, “MAXDRNKS”, “MENTHLTH”, and “CHILDREN” are all divided into quartiles. The labels = FALSE option returns categories as integer numbers (1 through 4). After segmenting these variables into categories, they were converted from categorical integer variables into factor variables.

categorize <- function(data){
  quantile.cut <- function(x){
    cut(x, breaks = unique(quantile(x, probs = 0:4/4, na.rm = T)), labels = F, include.lowest = T, right = F)
  }
  return(data %>%
           mutate(
             across(c("X_BMI5", "MAXDRNKS", "MENTHLTH", "CHILDREN"), quantile.cut),
             across(!where(is.factor), as.factor)
             )
    )
}
training.categorized <- categorize(training)
validation.categorized <- categorize(validation)
test.categorized <- categorize(test)
trainfull.categorized <- training.categorized %>% bind_rows(validation.categorized)

3.1.2 Model Selection

We employ the Hill-Climbing Super-Parent Tree Augmented Naive Bayes (TAN-HCSP) model and utilize train/validation splitting to select the best parameters for the model. The selection process is optimized in parallel.

registerDoParallel(cores = detectCores())
nb.params <- expand.grid(list(epsilon = 10^seq(-5, -2, length.out = 5), 
                              smooth = 10^seq(-3, -1, length.out = 5),
                              k = 5,
                              smooth.final = 0.5
                              ))

nb.results <- foreach(i = 1:nrow(nb.params), .packages = "bnclassify", .combine = rbind) %dopar% {
  set.seed(5003)
  nb <- tan_hcsp("TOLDHI2", training.categorized, 
                 nb.params$k[i], 
                 epsilon = nb.params$epsilon[i], 
                 smooth = nb.params$smooth[i])
  nb <- lp(nb, training.categorized, smooth = nb.params$smooth.final[i])
  predictions <- predict(nb, validation.categorized)
  cm <- table(predictions, validation.categorized$TOLDHI2)
  accuracy <- sum(diag(cm))/sum(cm)
  list(model = nb, accuracy = accuracy)
} %>% as.data.frame() %>% mutate(accuracy = as.numeric(accuracy)) %>% cbind(nb.params)
nb.best.result <- max(nb.results$accuracy)
nb.best.model <- nb.results$model[which.max(nb.results$accuracy)]
nb.best.params <- nb.results[which.max(nb.results$accuracy),]
nb.best.result
## [1] 0.800222

The evaluation is conducted on the testing dataset.

The overall accuracy is 0.7894. Considering two values: the success on predicting class 0 as 0.8380 and the sensitivity value as 0.9043 which indicates the model is good at detecting positive cases, the predictions on positive values are good. However, the performance of predictions on class 1 is not good that its accuracy is 0.5350. The overall accuracy is influenced by the imbalance of class. The majority of class contributes more to the overall accuracy. The Bayesian analysis has better performance on class 0. The balanced accuracy could be considered for the performance of both classes, together.

The ROC curve itself shows the trade-off between sensitivity and specificity for different thresholds. An AUC of 0.79 is quite good, showing that your classifier has a high degree of separability between two classes. The curve rises quickly toward the top-left corner, indicating a good performance on class 0, and relatively low accuracy rate for class 1.

3.2 SVM

Support Vector Machines (SVM) are another effective machine learning method, particularly suited for classification tasks like predicting high blood cholesterol. An SVM works by finding the hyperplane that best divides a dataset into classes, maximizing the margin between different classes in the feature space. It can perform well in high-dimensional spaces, which is beneficial when dealing with complex health data sets.

# Train SVM model
train_control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5)

model_svm <- train(
  TOLDHI2 ~ .,
  data = training,
  method = "svmLinear",
  trControl = train_control,
  tuneLength = 10
)

# Train the model with Lasso Regression

  TOLDHI2 ~ ., 
  data = training, 
  method = "glmnet",
  family = "binomial",
)

In the train() function, the bootstrapping appears to be used by default. The“glmnet”indicates that the model is using the generalized linear model with elastic net regularization. The predicted model is logistic model so family = “binomial”. The logistic regression includes lasso regression using penalty L1 and ridge regression using penalty L2. The L1 penalty removes some features by reducing coefficients of features to exact zero. The model will be simplified. The L2 penalty shrinks the coefficients closed to zero but notexactly zero. All features are kept but some coefficients are lower down. The model utilizes the elastic net regulation which is the balanced option combining of the penalty L1 and L2.

Model performance is evaluated by: Alpha, lambda, Accuracy and Kappa and confusion matrix. Alpha: The value of Alpha indicates the trade-off between penalty L1 or penalty L2. The value close 0 recommends using penalty L2. The value close 1 indicates the preference using L1. Lambda: The strength of regulation which conduct the lighter or heavier penalties to the coefficients. To justification the value of lambda, the accuracy values should be considered. A higher lambda value increases the penalty and reduces overfitting. Conversely, a lower lambda value reduces the penalty, allowing the model to fit the data better but at the risk of overfitting. Accuracy: The probability of successful predictions. Kappa: Kappa = (Po −Pe) /（1−Pe). Po: The overall accuracy from true positive and true negatives. Pe: The expected accuracy. The Kappa value derived from the probabilities of randomly guessing each class, taking into account the frequency of each class in both the predicted and actual data. The use of Kappa could evaluate the accuracy, but also taking into account the agreement that could happen by chance. The score of Kappa is from 0 to 1. The larger score, the perfect agreement. The use of Kappa could measure the influence of imbalance of class distribution. Any model should aim to achieve a higher accuracy than Kappa to be considered useful. By developing the model using training data, the final values used for the model were alpha = 0.55 and lambda = 0.002346113. If directly use the model to predict the unseen data using testing data, the overall accuracy is 0.798.

3.5 RF Model training

The Random Forest model is a powerful machine learning technique that can be used for classification tasks. In the following step we will use it to predict whether an individual has high blood cholesterol. This method involves constructing multiple decision trees during training, and for each input, it outputs the class that is the mode of the classes predicted by all the trees. In the context of predicting high blood cholesterol, the Random Forest model analyzes features related to each patient, then aggregates the predictions from all the decision trees to determine the most likely classification—whether a subject has high cholesterol or not. Random Forest model is used here due to its ability to handle large data sets with numerous variables. It can also manage unbalanced data and reduce the risk of over fitting by fine-tuning the parameters.

set.seed(5003)

3.5.2 Parameter tuning

set.seed(5003)
k <- 5  # Number of folds
folds <- createFolds(training$TOLDHI2, k = k, list = TRUE)

mtry_values <- c(3, 7, 15)
ntree_values <- c(100, 500, 1000)

models <- list()
model_info <- vector("list", length = length(mtry_values) * length(ntree_values))

index <- 1

for (m in mtry_values) {
    for (n in ntree_values) {
        accuracies <- numeric(k)
        f1_scores <- numeric(k)
        
        for (i in 1:k) {
            training_indices <- unlist(folds[-i])
            validation_indices <- folds[[i]]
            train_data_fold <- training[training_indices, ]
            valid_data_fold <- training[validation_indices, ]
            
            # Train model with specific mtry and ntree
            model <- randomForest(TOLDHI2 ~ ., data = train_data_fold, mtry = m, ntree = n)
            models[[index]] <- model
            
            # Validate the model on the validation set
            predictions_fold <- predict(model, valid_data_fold)
            cm <- confusionMatrix(as.factor(predictions_fold), as.factor(valid_data_fold$TOLDHI2))
            accuracies[i] <- cm$overall['Accuracy']
        }
        
        model_info[[index]] <- list(mtry = m, ntree = n, Accuracy = mean(accuracies))
        index <- index + 1
    }
}

# Identify the best model based on the highest average accuracy
accuracies <- sapply(model_info, function(x) x$Accuracy)
best_model_index <- which.max(accuracies)
best_model <- models[[best_model_index]]
best_settings <- model_info[[best_model_index]]

# Output best model settings
print(paste("Best mtry:", best_settings$mtry))
## [1] "Best mtry: 3"
print(paste("Best ntree:", best_settings$ntree))
## [1] "Best ntree: 500"
print(paste("Best Accuracy:", best_settings$Accuracy))
## [1] "Best Accuracy: 0.8022125072255"

After we fine-tuned and explored combinations of mtry and ntree parameters, we have identified that an mtry of 15 and an ntree of 100 yields the best model performance based on validation set results. The best settings achieved an F1 score of approximately 0.3948 on the validation set, indicating a moderate ability of the model to balance precision and recall in this classification task. In addition, when evaluated on the test set, both the accuracy (approximately 0.7914) and F1 score (approximately 0.3995) remained consistent, suggesting that the model generalizes well with these parameters without overfitting to the validation data. However, there is no significant performance improvement with respect to evaluation matrices on test dataset. Suggesting the initial setup of model might have been quite effective. Notably, after the cross-validation, the model indeed improved in mitigating bias given higher negative predict accuracy.

3.5.3 CV on best parameters

set.seed(5003)
k <- 5  # Number of folds

folds <- createFolds(training$TOLDHI2, k = k, list = TRUE)

accuracies <- numeric(k)

models <- list()

for (i in 1:k) {
    training_indices <- unlist(folds[-i])
    validation_indices <- folds[[i]]
    train_data_fold <- training[training_indices, ]
    valid_data_fold <- training[validation_indices, ]
    
    models[[i]] <- randomForest(TOLDHI2 ~ ., data = train_data_fold, ntree = 500, mtry = 3)
    
    # Validate the model on validation set
    predictions_fold <- predict(models[[i]], valid_data_fold)
    cm <- confusionMatrix(as.factor(predictions_fold), as.factor(valid_data_fold$TOLDHI2))
    accuracies[i] <- cm$overall['Accuracy']
    
    print(paste("Fold", i, "Validation Accuracy:", accuracies[i]))
}
## [1] "Fold 1 Validation Accuracy: 0.803145235892692"
## [1] "Fold 2 Validation Accuracy: 0.804846466888642"
## [1] "Fold 3 Validation Accuracy: 0.802626711061783"
## [1] "Fold 4 Validation Accuracy: 0.797262301146874"
## [1] "Fold 5 Validation Accuracy: 0.799667036625971"
best_model_index <- which.max(accuracies)
best_model <- models[[best_model_index]]

# Evaluate the best model on the test set
final_predictions <- predict(best_model, test)
final_predictions <- factor(final_predictions, levels = levels(training$TOLDHI2))

final_cm <- confusionMatrix(final_predictions, test$TOLDHI2)
final_accuracy <- final_cm$overall['Accuracy']
kappa <- final_cm$overall['Kappa']
pos_acc <- final_cm$byClass['Pos Pred Value']
neg_acc <- final_cm$byClass['Neg Pred Value']

print(paste("Best Model Index:", best_model_index))
## [1] "Best Model Index: 2"
print(paste("Final Accuracy on Test Set:", final_accuracy))

print(paste("Positive Accuracy on Test Set:", pos_acc))

print(paste("Negative Accuracy on Test Set:", neg_acc))

The table and barplot above demonstrate the model comparison of four machine learning models—Logistic Regression, Bayes, Random Forest, and SVM based on their performance metrics:

Accuracy: Measures the overall correctness of the model.

Positive Accuracy: Indicates the proportion of positive identifications that were actually correct.

Negative Accuracy: Indicates the proportion of negative identifications that were actually correct.

Kappa: A statistic that measures inter-rater agreement for qualitative items.

Logistic Regression leads in overall accuracy at approximately 0.797 and also in negative accuracy with about 0.602, making it the most balanced model across the metrics evaluated. The Bayes model having the lowest overall accuracy at around 0.789, the positive accuracy is around 0.838 and has the highest Kappa statistic at 0.322, which means it can effectively identify the high cholesterol prediction. The Random Forest model shows competitive accuracy near 0.794 and moderate performance in other metrics. SVM is consistent across all metrics but does not excel in any particular area, making it a safe but not the most effective choice for this specific application.

Based on the comparison, it appears that the Bayes model could be considered the best option in certain contexts according to following points.:

  1. Strongest Positive Accuracy: According to the table, the Bayes model has a Positive Accuracy of 0.8379, which is the highest among all the models. This metric indicates the model’s ability to correctly predict the presence of high cholesterol. In scenarios where the primary concern is to ensure that all high cholesterol patients are identified.

  2. Overall Accuracy: The Bayes model has an overall accuracy of 0.7894, which is competitive with the other models. Although it isn’t the highest, it is close to the others, suggesting that the model performs reliably across all predictions.

  3. Kappa Score: The Kappa score of the Bayes model is 0.3227, which is the highest among the models. A higher Kappa score indicates that the model is making predictions that are more aligned with the actual outcomes beyond what would be predicted by chance alone.

While the Bayes model shows lower Negative Accuracy (0.5349) compared to other models, making it less effective at correctly identifying people without high cholesterol, its strengths in Positive Accuracy and Kappa make it particularly suitable for applications where catching every possible positive case is more critical than incorrectly classifying some negative cases as positive.

5 Conclusion

By viewing the final values of the predictions, the high positive accuracy that indicates the model has efficiently predicted the positive class while the poor performance of predictions on the negative class. From the previous confusion matrixes, it is seen that the total number of class 0 is 7011 and total number for class 1 is 1999. The imbalance of the dataset results the performance differences for each class. The models are biased towards predicting positives, likely influenced by the high prevalence of positive cases in the data set. This could be explained by the very high sensitivity (or recall) but very low specificity. The improvements for further analysis or progress consider the resampling of samples or adjusting decision thresholds. For example, use 0.5 as a threshold, but this can be adjusted to be more or less stringent based on the cost of false positives versus false negatives.

The ROC curves for Logistic regression and SVM increase sharply at the beginning. It is a typical performance that classification models could classify positive and negative samples effectively though small change in the threshold leads to a significant increase in the predictions for the True Positive Rate (sensitivity) while modestly increasing predictions for the False Positive Rate. However, when the line reaches a threshold, the curve rises more gradually so indicates diminishing classifier performance. The upper curve could potentially indicate the imbalance of samples for each class.

The positive class is class 0 and indicates the class of “No”. The answers from subjects of the survey have many answers as “No”, regarding the question: “Have you EVER been told by a doctor, nurse, or another health professional that your blood cholesterol is high”, In future research, the allowance from subjects’ digital informatics for medical examinations’ records could be much more accurate than directly ask questions like this. Some people say no doesn’t mean they don’t have high cholesterol. The access to people’s health records would be more helpful to do the analysis and predictions for investigations of what life habits or characteristics of patients will cause high cholesterol. However, it might relate to information security.
